## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: a single fail-soft JSONL logging hook at the
  http-post layer is sufficient to diagnose the protocol mismatches
  that have bitten us so far (vector-vs-list parsing, streaming
  chunk handling, OTLP unit-suffix derivation), without
  instrumenting individual call sites or building a custom proxy.

## Validation
- The bug we shipped this against (streaming tool_calls in the
  first chunk) was caught by directly inspecting an http.jsonl
  trace from a successful sage tool-call demo. The first_chunk
  field showed the tool_calls shape; the last_chunk field showed
  the empty done:true message. That was the smoking gun.
- Bearer token redaction verified by an explicit test that
  attempts to leak \"Bearer SECRET-TOKEN-XYZ\" through the
  Authorization header and asserts the log line contains
  <redacted> instead of the secret string.
- 12 entries captured cleanly per chat turn — not so many that
  the file becomes unwieldy for a debugging session.

## Refutation / known limits
- Streaming responses only capture first_chunk and last_chunk,
  not the full chunk sequence. For a 50-chunk SSE stream we'd
  miss intermediate state. Acceptable for current use cases
  (Ollama tool calls fit in 2-5 chunks); will need extension
  for MCP SSE work in 0.7.0 where intermediate chunks may carry
  notification frames.
- Body truncation at 8192 chars (unless SAGE_DEBUG_HTTP_FULL=1)
  could hide bugs in very large requests. The full bypass exists
  for forensic captures.
- Failure mode: if .logs/ is on a full disk, the silent catch
  swallows the write error. We won't notice the log isn't being
  written. Acceptable trade-off vs breaking the REPL.
- The wrapper adds an extra getenv call per http-post even when
  disabled. Profile-trivial but worth knowing.
- POST-only. http-get is NOT instrumented because we don't
  currently use it for any debug-relevant traffic. MCP SSE will
  need GET instrumentation in 0.7.0.

